Cybercrime Case Study – Phishing Attack

Phishing is a type of cybercrime where attackers try to trick people into revealing personal information such as passwords, bank details, or OTPs. This usually happens through fake emails, messages, or websites that look official.

In a typical phishing attack, a student may receive an email that looks like it is from a bank or a popular website. The email may say that their account will be blocked unless they click a link and update their details. When the student clicks the link, it opens a fake website that looks real. The student enters their username, password, and OTP. The attacker then uses this information to access the student’s bank account and steal money.

Students and elderly people are common targets because they may not always recognize fake emails or links. The consequences of phishing include financial loss, identity theft, and loss of personal data.

This case study shows that people should always check the sender’s email address, avoid clicking suspicious links, and never share OTPs or passwords online.
